occupational name for an archer, from Middle Low German <i>schutten</i> ‘to shoot’. Compare   Schuetz  .","Dutch: variant of   Schut  , a cognate of 1 above.","Germanized form of Croatian and Slovenian <b>Šute</b>, and probably also of its cognate <b>Šutej</b> (see   Shutey  ). In part, it is a Gottscheerish (i.e. Gottschee German) surname, originating from the Kočevsko region in Lower Carniola, Slovenia (see   Kocevar  ). The surname <i>Šute</i> has died out in Slovenia."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When David Chute was born in 1540, in Willesborough, Kent, England, United Kingdom, his father, Philip FitzEdward Chowte, was 15 and his mother, Johanna Girling, was 20. He had at least 1 daughter with Judith Ruth Searl. He died in 1595, in Carlisle, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1540–1595":"1540–1595","1540–Female":"1540–Surnud","1562–1607":"1562–1607","1525–1566":"1525–1566","1520–Female":"1520–Surnud","1525":"1525","1566":"1566","5 Apr. 1566":"5. aprill 1566","1520":"1520","1540":"1540","156